  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The preprint titled \"KMT2A oncoproteins induce epigenetic resistance to targeted therapies\" by Derek H. Janssens et al. has established a foundation for further inquiry into the complexities of targeted cancer therapies. With six citations already, it demonstrates its growing traction within the academic community.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Derek H. Janssens and colleagues' preprint on KMT2A oncoproteins highlights significant insights into how these proteins can instigate epigenetic resistance to targeted therapies. This research, hosted on bioRxiv, originates from several key institutions, including Baylor College of Medicine and St. Jude Children's Research Hospital, emphasizing its robust scientific foundation and collaboration among leading experts in the field.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Though direct public engagement metrics, such as mentions on social media platforms or Wikipedia, are absent, the academic citations indicate a positive reception within the scholarly community. The work has sparked interest across various esteemed journals, including \"Cancers\" and \"Medical Oncology,\" where it has found relevance to ongoing discussions in cancer research.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The engagement with the research is further underscored by its proven downstream reuse, as indicated by the seven instances of subsequent research that have leveraged the findings and concepts presented in this study. This highlights the research's significance not only in its immediate scope but also in its broader implications for the ongoing exploration of epigenetic factors in cancer therapy.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, while the extent of public discourse remains limited, the early academic impact of this preprint suggests that the study is influencing cutting-edge inquiries within the field of cancer research. Its contributions are likely to foster a deeper understanding of therapeutic resistance mechanisms, thus underscoring the critical importance of ongoing investigation in this domain.</p>",
